"# Appendix F — Voice mixing recipes

Ten concrete voice-16 mixes with musical explanation. Each recipe: instrument assignments to voices 1-15 and a mixer routing on voice 16.

Every recipe uses `composer/voice-pool` and `composer/voice-mix-set` (v1.1). The pool exposes 16 voices; voice 16 mixes.

## Recipe 1 — Drum bus

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument snare))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument hihat-closed))
(composer/voice-assign pool 4 '(:instrument hihat-open))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3 4))
```

All drums into the mixer. Apply reverb + gentle compression on the mixer's output. Bass and lead voices bypass and stay dry.

## Recipe 2 — Vocal-double

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument voice-lead))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument voice-lead :pitch-shift -12))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2))
```

Lead voice and an octave-down voice. Mix them for a thick vocal-double effect.

## Recipe 3 — Chord stack

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument sine :pitch C4))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument sine :pitch E4))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument sine :pitch G4))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3))
```

Three sine tones stacked to a major triad. Route through the mixer for shared envelope shaping.

## Recipe 4 — Split lead / bass

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument lead))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument bass))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '())
```

Empty mix. Lead and bass play direct. Use when you want independent processing per voice.

## Recipe 5 — Drums + bass together, lead solo

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument snare))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument bass))
(composer/voice-assign pool 4 '(:instrument lead))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3))
```

Rhythm section (kick, snare, bass) through the mixer. Lead voice bypasses. Solo the lead by muting the mixer.

## Recipe 6 — Detune-thick pad

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument saw :detune 0))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument saw :detune 7))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument saw :detune -7))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2 3))
```

Three saw voices at slightly different detunes for a wide analog-pad feel. Mixed together, they beat against each other.

## Recipe 7 — Polyphonic keyboard (up to 15 voices)

Leave the pool with default (:oldest) steal policy. Play chords via `(note :instrument piano :pitch X)` — the runtime allocates voices from the pool. When more than 15 notes want to play at once, the oldest voice yields.

```scheme
(composer/voice-pool :bind '(cart :pool) :steal 'oldest)
;; no explicit assignments; runtime allocates as notes fire
```

Fifteen-note polyphony, one mixer for master effects.

## Recipe 8 — Kick + snare mix, hats bypass

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument snare))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument hihat))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(1 2))
```

Kick and snare go through the mixer (for compression, for shared reverb). Hats bypass — their high frequencies survive without processing.

## Recipe 9 — Dry drums, wet everything else

```scheme
(composer/voice-assign pool 1 '(:instrument kick))
(composer/voice-assign pool 2 '(:instrument snare))
(composer/voice-assign pool 3 '(:instrument pad))
(composer/voice-assign pool 4 '(:instrument lead))
(composer/voice-mix-set pool '(3 4))
```

Pad and lead go through the mixer with reverb; drums stay dry. Inverse of Recipe 5.

## Recipe 10 — Sub-mixer via voice/mix in fx-chain

Combine `voice/mix` with an fx-chain applied at the mixer output:

```scheme
(voice/mix '(1 2 3) 0.75)  ;; returns a voice-mix record with gain 0.75
```

The runtime routes the referenced voices through a shared gain and then through the mixer's fx chain. Use this to build sub-mixers for a stems-style workflow (drums stem, bass stem, lead stem, all mixed through separate voice/mix records into voice 16).

## The mixer's role

Voice 16 is not just polyphony bookkeeping. It is a routing bus. Everything you route through it shares:

- The mixer's fx chain (if you set one).
- The mixer's gain.
- The mixer's steal behavior (which is nothing — voice 16 does not steal, it accumulates).

Voices that bypass the mixer keep their individual signals and their individual fx chains.

## Voice-steal policy in practice

At `:steal 'oldest` (the default), when a new note wants a voice and all 15 are busy, the oldest voice yields. This is what most musicians expect — the sound that has been playing longest is the least perceptually important.

At `:steal 'quietest`, the voice with the lowest current velocity yields. Better for chord fingering where you want to keep the loudest notes.

At `:steal 'newest`, the newest voice yields. Rare. Useful only for niche cases where you want to preserve sustained voices at all costs.

## The mixer is optional

If your song only needs 4 or 8 voices with no shared processing, skip the mixer. The voice pool still enforces the polyphony cap; voice 16 sits idle.

The mixer becomes valuable when you want:

- Shared reverb over a group.
- Shared compression on drums.
- A stereo sub-mix.
- Per-stem gain rides.

## What the mixer does not do

The mixer does NOT:

- Route through a chain of sub-mixers (it is one bus, not a tree).
- Add its own effects automatically (you attach fx to the mixer voice explicitly).
- Convert mono to stereo (a v2 direction, not v1.1).

## Verified

Every construction in this appendix was verified as a widget/verb call against `bin/motoi eval` v1.1. The full runtime behavior of voice-16 as an audio mixer depends on the runtime's audio graph, which is the audio-engine's affair; the composer's role is to record the routing.

## Where the voice-pool code lives

`lib/composer/composer-v11.js` — `makeVoicePool`, `voicePoolAssign`, `voicePoolSetMix`, `emitVoicePoolDeclaration`, `applyFormToVoicePool`. See Chapter 12 for the widget in depth.
")
